column10: It seemed like the robot didn't learn anything to be entirely honest.
Definitely took much less effort than Method A to correct the robot's movement and it seemed to adapt to my changes unlike Method A which really didn't.
The robot continuously fought me on every correction I tried to make leading me to feel like I needed at least a finger near one of the offending joints at all times.

The no-spill experiment was most surprising it required very little interaction to get the robot to do what I desired. It was much trickier to get the robot to do what I wanted in the height experiment. The laptop experiment fell somewhere in the middle.

While I did not feel like the robot was fighting my corrections I also corrected it in such a way that didn't really give the robot a chance to demonstrate its "understanding." This is why I could not rate it higher in terms of "understanding"/"collaboration".
The robot had an idea of what it was going to do and it worked against my corrections trying to get back on "it's pre-chosen track" whenever I stopped correcting it.
I felt as though results of my interactions were inconsistent between the two trials sometimes pleasantly surprising and sometimes not "it's fighting me!"

Method B felt like it had a more natural understanding of motion; I was able to guide it as if it were a human arm instead of tugging it around joint-by-joint. It also felt like method B incorporated my feedback into its trajectory plan while method A just kept returning to the spot I didn't want it resulting in more of a "swat it away" interaction instead of a "show it how it's done"
between trials the response felt inconsistent
had to apply more force--felt as though it were fighting me to carry out the task the way it would normally perform it

Most of the time the robot required minimal corrections. If I pushed it hard enough sometimes it would seem to fall into another mode and then do things correctly. Other times I'd move it and it'd be "sticky" coming back to the original trajectory and I kept having to correct it again. This stickiness was only really happening on the last task though where I was trying to keep it from hitting the laptop; otherwise it corrected pretty well. (Though not between trials.)
Robot didn't respond to corrections-- went back to previous path. It made it easy to predict though because it just meant I had to keep on correcting it periodically.
The robot allowed me to correct its motion as it went but didn't seem to really take the hint as to what I was trying to get it to do..
Once I gave it a little correction the robot seemed to quickly figure out what I cared about and kept doing it on its own. It was pretty satisfying!
